				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">Ok here's the actual breakdown of the $87 billion: <a href="http://uk.biz.yahoo.com/030908/80/e7twl.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">http://uk.biz.yahoo.com/030908/80/e7twl.html</a>
<br />

<br />
Coincidentally this is a "one time charge" not a recurring program along the lines of say Medicare where it's an ongoing program.  Yes he might come back and ask for more but so will medicare also eventually the rebuilding will taper out.  What I also found surprising is that the $87 bil. isn't just for Iraq but also for Afganistan as well.  Whether you agree with the invasion or not you have to see that we can't go in, gut a government and just leave or those that were driven out will just walk back into power and all that money spent doing the invading would be redundant and pointless.  Better to make sure, if you're going to make changes, that those changes stick the first time around.  Otherwise we might very well find ourselves in the years ahead doing the same thing all over again.
<br />

<br />
Also let's put this money in perspective.  The national budget is what? About 2.2 trillion dollars?  So that's puts $87 billion somewhere around 5% give or take? (I suck at math so I'm guestimating here, please feel free to give more accurate percentages there).  So let's compare it to other programs.  The upcoming prescription drug package is said to cost *at least* 400 billion in the first 10 years but some analysts including those quoting that number say it's more likely to be double that.
<br />
<a href="http://209.157.64.200/focus/f-news/935073/posts" target="_blank" class="postlink">http://209.157.64.200/focus/f-news/935073/posts</a>
<br />

<br />
To top it all off many opponents are saying lets spend the money on education instead.  Now education will use approx $63 billion of the 2004 budget.  Just $20 billion shy of the one time request of $87 billion.  <a href="http://www.ed.gov/about/overview/budget/index.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">http://www.ed.gov/about/overview/budget/index.html</a> Seems like alot till you remember we're talking about a $2.2 trillion budget.  It's should also be noted that the US spends more money per child *already* than any other nation in the world.  On top of that we're nowhere near the top as far as results go. Here's an AP article to explain better what I'm talking about: <a href="http://www.timesdispatch.com/frontpage/MGB1B73POKD.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">http://www.timesdispatch.com/frontpage/MGB1B73POKD.html</a>.  Maybe it's time to start thinking about how we can teach our children better rather than how much more money we can dump into a failing system.
<br />

<br />
And really when you look at it...87 billion is alot of money but honestly (to me) it's worth it if we don't have to deal with a guy like Saddam anymore.<span class="gensmall"></span>


				</div></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
