				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">I can't argue with the use of the cash in Afghanistan.  However, if you want to use 86 billion to protect the USA from terrorism how about these things to start (just quick rattling off the top of my tiny brain)? 
<br />
1. Greasing some palms in Pakistan to clean up the terrorist ties in the North.
<br />
2. Dealing with the banks in the UAE who move the money for terrorists.
<br />
3. Forming business and political ties with the wealthy families in Kuwait and Saudi Arabia who support terrorism.
<br />
4. Cleaning up record keeping in the USA and Russia for biological and chemical components.
<br />
5. Gifting the Shi'ites and Kurds with millions in fancy gear and let them throw the country into turmoil so it has other things to worry about than the USA.
<br />
These things have undoubtedly been tossed around by some bright folks in government.  Maybe someone has information or reasons why they were discussed and decided against?
<br />

<br />

<br />
The $86 billion is supposed to be a one time fee.  It is the second request so far though.  It represents almost 20% of the projected US defecit.  I  don't think that the USA will ever be able to pull out of Iraq.  It would create a larger mess than is there now and Iraq would present a far greater danger to the USA than before the war.  Iraq did not have WMD, did not contribute to terrorism in the US, and did not target the US before the war.  You can sure bet they will work on all that if the USA pulls out now though.  The USA has created a fanatic enemy for generations to come. 
<br />

<br />
Trying to put in a government that fits Western ideals in the Middle East is like cramming the square peg into a round hole.  When a nation goes to war with another that has a culture and set of ideals so different from its own, it must be willing to follow the war to its terrible conclusion.  The USA has been unwilling to do this and now stability in the Middle East will require a continual presence and a lot more requests for money.  The war was stupid.  The finances of the war are stupid.  But the USA (and other nations by association) are stuck with it now.<span class="gensmall"></span>


